Seugnet Van Zyl, Netwerk24Belinda Louw (ILovePix via Netwerk24) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Pretoria &ndash; The carwash employee who caused the death a woman and her unborn baby in August has not been charged yet,&nbsp;Netwerk24&nbsp;reported on Tuesday. The man wanted to move a Toyota Fortuner from one part of the carwash at a Gezina, Pretoria, filling station to another. He did not have permission to drive the vehicle.He lost control of it and drove over Belinda Louw, 35, who was in the waiting area.&nbsp;She was 38-weeks pregnant. Her unborn child died soon after the accident and Louw died in hospital eight days later.&nbsp;The boy would have been called Ryan. He was scheduled to be born via caesarean section six days later.Mother and child were buried together on September 1.&nbsp;Police spokesperson Captain Coba Brits said police were still waiting for a pathology report before they could get a warrant for the man&rsquo;s arrest.They initially investigated a charge of reckless or negligent driving, but changed it to culpable homicide after Louw&rsquo;s death.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.